04473nam a22007695i 9780231537513DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20142014nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2014010612  a97802315375137 a10.7312/burd169282doi  a(DE-B1597)458265  a(OCoLC)979739475  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aLA1081b.B87 2015 7aPOL0540002bisacsh04a3002231 aBurde, Dana, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSchools for Conflict or for Peace in Afghanistan /cDana Burde. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (232 p.) :b‹B›Maps: ‹/B›3,, ‹B›Figures: ‹/B›3.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tTime Line. Education in Modern Afghan History -- t1. Introduction -- t2. Humanitarian Action and the Neglect of Education -- t3. Jihad Literacy -- t4. Education for Stability -- t5. Education for the World -- t6. Conclusion. Education as Hope -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aForeign-backed funding for education does not always stabilize a country and enhance its statebuilding efforts. Dana Burde shows how aid to education in Afghanistan bolstered conflict both deliberately in the 1980s through violence-infused, anti-Soviet curricula and inadvertently in the 2000s through misguided stabilization programs. She also reveals how dominant humanitarian models that determine what counts as appropriate aid have limited attention and resources toward education, in some cases fueling programs that undermine their goals.For education to promote peace in Afghanistan, Burde argues we must expand equal access to quality community-based education and support programs that increase girls' and boys' attendance at school. Referring to a recent U.S. effort that has produced strong results in these areas, Burde commends the program's efficient administration and good quality, and its neutral curriculum, which can reduce conflict and build peace in lasting ways. Drawing on up-to-date research on humanitarian education work amid conflict zones around the world and incorporating insights gleaned from extensive fieldwork in Afghanistan and Pakistan, Burde recalculates and improves a popular formula for peace.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aEconomic assistance, AmericanzAfghanistan. 0aEducation and statezAfghanistan. 0aEducationzAfghanistan. 0aHumanitarian assistance, AmericanzAfghanistan. 0aNation-buildingzAfghanistan. 0aSchoolszAfghanistan. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Asian.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066586440uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/burd1692840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231537513423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231537513/original  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  a978-3-11-066586-4  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK